-- ── Healthie ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Healthie is an API-first, ONC-certified EHR and practice management platform that gives digital health companies scheduling, billing, telehealth and patient engagement tools out of the box.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (per-clinician tiers, plus API add-on)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$19/month (Core plan)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2016, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$101-250 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$New York, New York, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Healthie Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Explore Healthie's API-first EHR platform in 2026: pricing plans, telehealth and billing features, GraphQL API, pros and cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Healthie is an API-first electronic health record (EHR) and practice management platform designed specifically for virtual-first and longitudinal care businesses, giving both individual practitioners and digital health startups a fully brandable, HIPAA-compliant infrastructure layer for scheduling, charting, billing, telehealth and patient engagement, accessible either through a ready-made web and mobile interface or entirely through Healthie's own API and SDKs. The company was founded in 2016 by CEO Erica Jain and CTO Cavan Klinsky, and is headquartered in New York City, where it has grown into a company of roughly 150 to 200 employees. Healthie's founding thesis was that a new generation of digital health companies, telehealth startups, coaching platforms, RDs, therapists and hybrid care businesses, needed EHR infrastructure they could embed into their own branded product rather than being forced onto a rigid, legacy, hospital-oriented EHR built for a completely different workflow. That thesis proved durable: by its own reporting, Healthie has grown to serve more than 45,000 clinicians delivering care to over 17 million patients across more than 25 longitudinal care specialties, spanning nutrition, mental health, physical therapy, chronic condition management and other virtual-first care models, and the company has stated it has been profitable for the majority of its history as a company even while raising outside capital. On the funding side, Healthie has raised more than 42 million dollars in total external capital from investors including TCV, Birchmere Ventures, Velvet Sea Ventures and Greymatter, with its most recent disclosed raise being a 23 million dollar Series B led by TCV, announced in October 2024, aimed at continuing to build out its infrastructure for longitudinal, virtual-first healthcare delivery. There has been no acquisition of Healthie by another company; it remains an independent, venture-backed private company. Technically, Healthie is built on a Ruby and PostgreSQL backend with React and React Native powering its web and mobile clients, and native Swift and Java components for iOS and Android respectively, and the platform is ONC Certified, meaning it meets the federal government's certification criteria for health IT used in programs tied to interoperability and quality reporting. Its defining architectural choice is a GraphQL API that exposes essentially the entire platform, scheduling, charting, insurance billing, telehealth, provider management and client engagement, as programmable infrastructure, and this is not a limited public-facing subset: it is described by the company as the same API its own internal teams use to build features across the web and mobile products. To make that API easier to consume, Healthie also ships pre-built React SDKs that give developers ready-made UI components for common workflows like scheduling or messaging, reducing the amount of custom frontend work needed to embed Healthie functionality into a third-party product. Core platform features include appointment scheduling with calendar sync, live video telehealth (including group telehealth sessions on higher tiers), integrated payment processing through Stripe, food and lifestyle journaling tools originally rooted in Healthie's dietitian and nutrition-coaching heritage, customizable intake and assessment forms, care plans and goal tracking, secure messaging between providers and clients, CMS-1500 insurance claim generation, outbound and inbound fax, and a native mobile app available free on both iOS and Android for providers and clients to use on the go. Pricing is structured around four core monthly tiers based primarily on active client count and feature depth. The Core plan starts at 19 dollars a month (18 dollars a month billed annually) and covers up to 10 active clients with scheduling, payments, charting, telehealth and the client portal and mobile app. The Essentials plan, Healthie's most popular tier, costs 49 dollars a month (45 dollars annually) and raises the client cap to 250 while adding free outbound fax, custom forms, CMS-1500 generation and group messaging, with ClaimMD insurance clearinghouse integration available as a 30-dollar-a-month add-on. The Plus plan, at 129 dollars a month (115 dollars annually), removes the client cap entirely and adds group telehealth, online programs and a dedicated inbound and outbound eFax line. The Group plan, starting at 149 dollars a month (135 dollars annually) and scaling with additional clinicians at 50 dollars a month per clinician, is built for multi-provider practices and adds a shared calendar, team member management, roles and permissions, internal staff chat and a dedicated support contact per provider. Across every tier, Healthie includes HIPAA and PCI compliance, core EHR charting, secure messaging, food and lifestyle journaling, care plans and goal tracking, and advanced reporting, with Stripe-processed payments carrying a standard 2.9 percent plus 30 cent transaction fee. The GraphQL API itself, along with more advanced integrations, is offered as an add-on primarily available to customers on the Group and higher-tier or Enterprise-style plans, reflecting Healthie's dual identity as both an off-the-shelf practice management tool for solo and small-group practitioners and a full infrastructure platform, marketed under the Healthie+ name, for digital health startups building their own branded product on top of it. Healthie's target customers span two distinct but related audiences: individual and small-group healthcare practitioners, particularly in nutrition, therapy, coaching and other virtual-first specialties, who want an easy-to-use, affordable, HIPAA-compliant EHR without a long implementation process, and digital health companies, startups and larger care organizations that need to spin up compliant clinical infrastructure quickly and prefer to build on an API rather than negotiate a multi-year contract with a legacy EHR vendor like Epic or athenahealth. Competitively, Healthie is most often compared to other EHR and practice management platforms serving allied health and virtual-first specialties, such as SimplePractice and TherapyNotes on the practitioner-facing side, and to platform infrastructure plays in digital health that offer similar API-first building blocks; Healthie differentiates itself through the breadth of specialties it serves under one roof, its ONC certification, and the fact that the same core platform can be consumed either as a polished ready-made app or as raw, fully programmable infrastructure via GraphQL, letting customers choose how much of the underlying EHR they want to expose to their own end users.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '8ca5d5be-9880-4ce7-94dd-56ab90d70f72';

