-- ── Heap ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Heap is a digital analytics platform that automatically captures every user interaction on web and mobile products, letting teams analyze behavior retroactively without manually instrumenting events.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (custom quote for paid tiers)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (up to 10,000 monthly sessions)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$201-500 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Heap Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Read our 2026 review of Heap by Contentsquare: autocapture analytics features, pricing tiers, session replay, pros and cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Heap, now operating as Heap by Contentsquare, is a digital analytics platform best known for pioneering autocapture: instead of requiring engineers to manually write tracking code for every button click, page view or form submission they want to measure, Heap automatically captures every user interaction across a web or mobile product from the moment it is installed, and lets analysts define and retroactively query the specific events they care about after the fact. That reversal of the traditional analytics workflow, capture everything first, define metrics later, was the company's original core insight and remains its primary differentiator against event-based tools that require deliberate, upfront instrumentation. Heap was founded in Silicon Valley in 2013 by Matin Movassate, a former Facebook product manager, and Ravi Parikh, and the company built its headquarters in San Francisco. Over its life as an independent venture-backed company, Heap raised a total of roughly 216 million dollars across six funding rounds, with its final and largest round being a 110 million dollar Series D in December 2021 led by Sixth Street, which valued the company at roughly 960 million dollars just under the widely watched unicorn threshold; other backers over the years included Menlo Ventures, NewView Capital, Goldman Sachs Asset Management and DTCP. That independent chapter ended in late 2023: on September 28, 2023, French customer experience analytics company Contentsquare announced a definitive agreement to acquire Heap, describing it as the largest acquisition in Contentsquare's history, and the deal closed in December 2023. Since then Heap has operated as a product line within Contentsquare rather than as a standalone company, with its go-to-market and roadmap increasingly folded into Contentsquare's broader experience analytics suite; the two companies have publicly framed the combination as bringing together Contentsquare's experience-analytics strength (heatmaps, session replay, frustration signals) with Heap's product-analytics strength (funnels, retention, autocapture-based event analysis) into what they call the future of experience analytics. Technically, Heap's core mechanism relies on a lightweight JavaScript or mobile SDK snippet installed once on a site or app, after which it begins recording every user interaction, clicks, taps, form submissions, page views and more, into a queryable event stream without any per-event code changes. Analysts and product managers can then go into Heap's interface and define virtual events after the fact, essentially telling Heap after the product has already shipped which specific interactions correspond to a meaningful business event, and immediately get historical data for that new definition going back to whenever tracking began, rather than waiting weeks to accumulate new data the way manually instrumented tools require. On top of that raw interaction stream, Heap layers standard product analytics capabilities: funnel analysis to see where users drop off in a multi-step flow, retention analysis to understand which cohorts keep coming back, path analysis to see the sequences users actually take through a product, and user- and account-level analytics for B2B teams that need to see engagement at the account rather than individual level. Session replay and heatmaps are available as an add-on capability layered on top of the core analytics product, letting teams watch recordings of individual sessions or visualize aggregate click and scroll behavior for sessions where replay was enabled, rather than being bundled by default into every tier. Heap's pricing structure has four tiers: Free, Growth, Pro and Premier. The Free tier is genuinely self-serve and requires no sales conversation, covering up to 10,000 monthly sessions with six months of data retention and core autocapture analytics, which is enough for early-stage products or small teams to get real value before ever talking to sales. Every tier above Free, Growth, Pro and Premier, is sold on a custom, contact-sales basis priced primarily on monthly session volume and committed to annually, with reported starting prices for the Growth tier around 3,600 dollars a year for teams that need higher session caps and longer data history. Growth unlocks unlimited users and reports, custom charting, CSV exports and 12 months of history; Pro adds deeper analysis capabilities such as account-level analytics and real-time alerting, with session replay available as a paid add-on; and Premier, the top tier, adds data warehouse integration, behavioral targeting capabilities and a dedicated customer success manager, along with the longest data retention and highest session ceilings. Heap's target customers are product, growth and marketing teams at B2B and B2C software companies who need to understand detailed user behavior, feature adoption, drop-off points and retention drivers without maintaining a large, brittle backlog of manually tagged tracking events, a category of pain particularly acute at companies whose product changes frequently enough that manually instrumented analytics tools constantly fall out of date. Competitively, Heap sits in the product analytics category alongside tools like Mixpanel, Amplitude and PostHog, and its primary differentiation within that set has historically been autocapture-first data collection versus those tools' more event-definition-first approaches, though several competitors have since added their own autocapture options. Since the Contentsquare acquisition, Heap's positioning has shifted further to emphasize its place inside a broader combined suite that pairs product analytics with Contentsquare's session replay, heatmaps and frustration-signal detection, aiming to give customers both the quantitative funnel-and-retention view Heap built its reputation on and the qualitative, visual session-level view that was traditionally Contentsquare's strength, all from one vendor rather than stitching together two separate point solutions.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'cba47027-91c4-4aeb-adf8-67c52b50f458';

