-- ── Helicone ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Helicone is an open-source LLM observability platform and AI gateway that logs, monitors and helps optimize the cost and performance of applications built on OpenAI, Anthropic and other LLM providers.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium (usage-based paid tiers)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Hobby plan, 10,000 requests/month)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2023, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$11-50 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, California, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Helicone Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Read our 2026 review of Helicone: open-source LLM observability and AI gateway features, pricing tiers, the Mintlify acquisition, pros, cons and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Helicone is an open-source LLM observability platform and AI gateway built to give developers a unified, one-line-of-code way to monitor, log, evaluate and optimize the cost and performance of applications built on large language models. Rather than requiring teams to build custom logging and cost-tracking pipelines around every LLM provider they use, Helicone sits as a proxy or SDK integration between an application and providers like OpenAI, Anthropic and others, capturing every request and response so teams get a unified view of latency, cost, token usage, error rates and user-level interaction data across all the LLM traffic flowing through their product. The company was founded in 2023 by Justin Torre and Cole Gottdank, and it went through Y Combinator's Winter 2023 batch, a credential that gave it early visibility and access to a network of AI-native startups that became some of its earliest and most demanding customers as LLM applications scaled in production. Helicone built its reputation on being genuinely open source, with its full platform code publicly available on GitHub, which mattered to a developer audience that was wary of routing sensitive prompt and completion data through a fully closed-source, black-box SaaS layer sitting between them and their model provider. Over roughly three years as an independent company, Helicone grew to process what the company describes as 14.2 trillion tokens and to serve over 16,000 organizations, spanning solo developers experimenting with LLM APIs up to funded AI-native startups running significant production traffic. In March 2026, Helicone's independent chapter ended: Mintlify, the AI-era documentation and developer-knowledge-infrastructure company, announced it had acquired Helicone, with Helicone's founders Justin Torre and Cole Gottdank joining Mintlify's San Francisco team. The stated rationale on both sides centered on Helicone already powering the AI interactions inside Mintlify's own products before the deal, and the acquisition being framed by both companies as combining Helicone's observability, cost tracking and routing infrastructure with Mintlify's broader push into AI-era knowledge infrastructure, unlocking more accurate and performant AI services, deeper analytics across AI interactions, and integrated multi-provider routing and fallback handling for Mintlify's platform. Following the acquisition, Helicone has continued operating in what the company describes as maintenance mode, meaning it keeps shipping security updates, bug fixes and support for new models, but its independent product roadmap and go-to-market motion are now folded into Mintlify's broader strategy rather than continuing as a fully separate standalone business. Technically, Helicone's core product functions as an AI gateway and observability layer: developers can integrate it either as a lightweight proxy that requests are routed through, or via SDKs and direct API integrations, and Helicone then captures structured logs of every request, including prompts, completions, latency, token counts, and derived cost figures calculated per model and provider. On top of raw logging, Helicone offers evaluation tooling to test and score model outputs, a query language called HQL (Helicone Query Language) for more advanced analysis of logged data on paid tiers, alerting for anomalies or cost spikes, and multi-provider routing and fallback handling so an application can automatically shift traffic between providers or models if one becomes unavailable or degraded. Pricing follows a four-tier structure. The Hobby tier is free and is designed for developers starting new AI projects, including 10,000 requests per month, 1 gigabyte of log storage, a single user seat and 7-day data retention, enough for early prototyping and small side projects without any cost. The Pro tier costs 79 dollars a month and targets growing development teams, offering unlimited seats, alerting, reporting and access to the HQL query language, with a base allotment of requests included and additional usage billed beyond that; it also extends data retention to one month and raises the log ingestion rate to roughly 1,000 events per minute. The Team tier costs 799 dollars a month and is aimed at scaling organizations, supporting up to five organizations under one account, SOC-2 and HIPAA compliance, three months of data retention and a log ingestion rate around 15,000 events per minute. The top Enterprise tier is custom-priced and adds a tailored master service agreement, SAML single sign-on, on-premises deployment options, forever data retention, the highest log ingestion ceilings around 30,000 events per minute, and volume-based discounting. Helicone also runs several discount programs layered on top of the standard tiers: startups under two years old with less than 5 million dollars in funding get 50 percent off their first year, non-profits receive discounts scaled to organization size, open-source projects can receive a 100-dollar annual credit, and students get complimentary access. Helicone's target audience is developers and engineering teams building production applications on top of LLM APIs, spanning solo indie developers who want free visibility into their OpenAI or Anthropic usage up through funded AI-native startups and larger organizations that need SOC-2 and HIPAA-compliant observability, cost governance and multi-provider routing at meaningful scale. Competitively, Helicone sits in the LLM observability and AI gateway category alongside tools like LangSmith, Langfuse, Portkey and Datadog's LLM observability features, and its core differentiation has been its open-source codebase, one-line-of-code integration model, and its combined identity as both an observability platform and an AI gateway capable of routing and fallback, rather than being purely a passive logging and analytics layer bolted on after the fact.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '5b558345-f62d-4c17-b8c6-88e78d8300a2';

